						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">OneCrudeDude wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't see how slowdown could possibly exist in a puzzle game, or what purpose it would serve.</div><br />Non-scrolling games with a controlled number of objects on screen are less likely to have large variations of CPU load, meaning that puzzle games are among the steadiest ones, if you ignore slowdowns caused by occasional screen-sized effects (which more likely result from the low PPU bandwidth than increased CPU load).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">They're flicker heavy (due to how the graphics are designed) and slowdown prone (due to the graphics being layered).</div><br />Actually, I'd say that the sprite layering is partly responsible for the flickering, but it can't really be blamed for the slowdowns... I'm pretty sure the games would still lag even if no layering was used.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">As for bullet time, I always thought it'd be a neat way to sweep slowdown under the rug</div><br />True.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">REAL TIME SLOW-MOTION</div><br />I'm pretty sure this is a contradiction.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">In that case, would it be possible to make the NES detect if slowdown is happening, and in turn make it darken the screen and make a &quot;beeeewww&quot; sound, to make it look Matrix-y?</div><br />Yes, perfectly possible. I wouldn't turn on bullet time at the first sight of a dropped frame though, I'd probably wait for a few of them close together (say, 5 out of the last 10 frames). The effect also shouldn't be turned off too soon, so after a minimum amount of bullet time the engine would wait for a number of consecutive frames without lag (but I'd still fake the lag to the player during that time, since it's bullet time).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

